{
    "title": "group theory and fsm",
    "html": "<div class=\"markdown prose w-full break-words dark:prose-invert dark\"><p data-start=\"0\" data-end=\"174\" class=\"\">Yes! There is a deep connection between <strong data-start=\"40\" data-end=\"89\">finite state machines (FSMs) and group theory</strong>, particularly through <strong data-start=\"112\" data-end=\"129\">group actions</strong>, <strong data-start=\"131\" data-end=\"148\">Cayley graphs</strong>, and <strong data-start=\"154\" data-end=\"173\">automata theory</strong>.</p>\n<h3 data-start=\"176\" data-end=\"222\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"180\" data-end=\"222\">1. Groups as State Transitions in FSMs</strong></h3>\n<p data-start=\"223\" data-end=\"300\" class=\"\">Let <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span> be a finite group with elements as states. Consider an FSM where:</p>\n<ul data-start=\"301\" data-end=\"680\">\n<li data-start=\"301\" data-end=\"363\" class=\"\" style=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"303\" data-end=\"363\" class=\"\">Each <strong data-start=\"308\" data-end=\"325\">group element</strong> <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>e</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">e \\in G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.5782em; vertical-align: -0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span> represents a <strong data-start=\"353\" data-end=\"362\">state</strong>.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"364\" data-end=\"451\" class=\"\" style=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"366\" data-end=\"451\" class=\"\">Each <strong data-start=\"371\" data-end=\"387\">input symbol</strong> <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f \\in G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.8889em; vertical-align: -0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right: 0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span> represents an <strong data-start=\"416\" data-end=\"429\">operation</strong> on the current state.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"452\" data-end=\"680\" class=\"\" style=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"454\" data-end=\"515\" class=\"\">The transition function is defined by group multiplication:</p>\n<span class=\"katex-display\" style=\"\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" display=\"block\"><semantics><mrow><mi>δ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>e</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>e</mi><mo>⋅</mo><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\delta(e, f) = e \\cdot f</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 1em; vertical-align: -0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right: 0.03785em;\">δ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right: 0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.4445em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⋅</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.8889em; vertical-align: -0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right: 0.10764em;\">f</span></span></span></span></span>\n<p data-start=\"555\" data-end=\"605\" class=\"\">which leads to another state <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>h</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">h</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">h</span></span></span></span> in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p data-start=\"609\" data-end=\"680\" class=\"\">This means each transition follows the structure of a <strong data-start=\"663\" data-end=\"679\">group action</strong>.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 data-start=\"682\" data-end=\"715\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"686\" data-end=\"715\">2. FSMs and Cayley Graphs</strong></h3>\n<ul data-start=\"716\" data-end=\"1195\">\n<li data-start=\"716\" data-end=\"926\" class=\"\" style=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"718\" data-end=\"824\" class=\"\">A <strong data-start=\"720\" data-end=\"736\">Cayley graph</strong> of a group <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span> (with a generating set <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right: 0.05764em;\">S</span></span></span></span>) is a <strong data-start=\"793\" data-end=\"817\">graph representation</strong> where:</p>\n<ul data-start=\"827\" data-end=\"926\">\n<li data-start=\"827\" data-end=\"863\" class=\"\" style=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"829\" data-end=\"863\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"829\" data-end=\"838\">Nodes</strong> are elements of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"866\" data-end=\"926\" class=\"\" style=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"868\" data-end=\"926\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"868\" data-end=\"877\">Edges</strong> represent multiplication by elements of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right: 0.05764em;\">S</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"927\" data-end=\"1195\" class=\"\" style=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"929\" data-end=\"996\" class=\"\">This is structurally similar to an FSM’s transition diagram, where:</p>\n<ul data-start=\"999\" data-end=\"1131\">\n<li data-start=\"999\" data-end=\"1029\" class=\"\" style=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"1001\" data-end=\"1029\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"1001\" data-end=\"1028\">States = Group elements</strong>.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"1032\" data-end=\"1087\" class=\"\" style=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"1034\" data-end=\"1087\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"1034\" data-end=\"1086\">Inputs = Group elements (or a generating subset)</strong>.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"1090\" data-end=\"1131\" class=\"\" style=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"1092\" data-end=\"1131\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"1092\" data-end=\"1130\">Transitions = Group multiplication</strong>.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p data-start=\"1135\" data-end=\"1195\" class=\"\">This makes FSMs a <strong data-start=\"1153\" data-end=\"1194\">graph-theoretic realization of groups</strong>.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 data-start=\"1197\" data-end=\"1244\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"1201\" data-end=\"1244\">3. Identity Element and Rejecting State</strong></h3>\n<ul data-start=\"1245\" data-end=\"1620\">\n<li data-start=\"1245\" data-end=\"1397\" class=\"\" style=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"1247\" data-end=\"1310\" class=\"\">The <strong data-start=\"1251\" data-end=\"1271\">identity element</strong> <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>e</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">e</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span></span></span></span> acts as a <strong data-start=\"1290\" data-end=\"1307\">neutral state</strong>:</p>\n<span class=\"katex-display\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" display=\"block\"><semantics><mrow><mi>e</mi><mo>⋅</mo><mi>f</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">e \\cdot f = f</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.4445em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⋅</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.8889em; vertical-align: -0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right: 0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.8889em; vertical-align: -0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right: 0.10764em;\">f</span></span></span></span></span>\n<p data-start=\"1339\" data-end=\"1397\" class=\"\">so starting at <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>e</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">e</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span></span></span></span>, applying <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.8889em; vertical-align: -0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right: 0.10764em;\">f</span></span></span></span> moves to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.8889em; vertical-align: -0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right: 0.10764em;\">f</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"1398\" data-end=\"1620\" class=\"\" style=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"1400\" data-end=\"1484\" class=\"\">A <strong data-start=\"1402\" data-end=\"1421\">rejecting state</strong> can be modeled by a special absorbing element <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">r</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right: 0.02778em;\">r</span></span></span></span> where:</p>\n<span class=\"katex-display\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" display=\"block\"><semantics><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>⋅</mo><mi>f</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>r</mi><mspace width=\"1em\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∀</mi><mi>f</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">r \\cdot f = r \\quad \\forall f \\in G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.4445em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right: 0.02778em;\">r</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⋅</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.8889em; vertical-align: -0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right: 0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.8889em; vertical-align: -0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right: 0.02778em;\">r</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 1em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∀</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right: 0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span></span>\n<p data-start=\"1535\" data-end=\"1620\" class=\"\">meaning once we reach <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">r</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right: 0.02778em;\">r</span></span></span></span>, we stay there forever (like a <strong data-start=\"1596\" data-end=\"1618\">trap state in FSMs</strong>).</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 data-start=\"1622\" data-end=\"1674\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"1626\" data-end=\"1674\">4. Example: Symmetric Group <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>S</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">S_n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.8333em; vertical-align: -0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right: 0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height: 0.1514em;\"><span style=\"top: -2.55em; margin-left: -0.0576em; margin-right: 0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height: 2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">&ZeroWidthSpace;</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height: 0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> as FSM</strong></h3>\n<p data-start=\"1675\" data-end=\"1875\" class=\"\">Consider the <strong data-start=\"1688\" data-end=\"1709\">permutation group</strong> <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>S</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">S_3</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.8333em; vertical-align: -0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right: 0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height: 0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top: -2.55em; margin-left: -0.0576em; margin-right: 0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height: 2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">3</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">&ZeroWidthSpace;</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height: 0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, which consists of all possible rearrangements of three elements. Its Cayley graph (with generators <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>12</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(12)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 1em; vertical-align: -0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">12</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>23</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(23)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 1em; vertical-align: -0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">23</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>) can be seen as an FSM where:</p>\n<ul data-start=\"1876\" data-end=\"2024\">\n<li data-start=\"1876\" data-end=\"1955\" class=\"\" style=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"1878\" data-end=\"1955\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"1878\" data-end=\"1888\">States</strong> are permutations (e.g., <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>e</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>12</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>23</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>123</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>132</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mo>…</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">e, (12), (23), (123), (132), \\dots</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 1em; vertical-align: -0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">12</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">23</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">123</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">132</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"minner\">…</span></span></span></span>).</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"1956\" data-end=\"2024\" class=\"\" style=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"1958\" data-end=\"2024\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"1958\" data-end=\"1973\">Transitions</strong> correspond to applying swaps (like input symbols).</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 data-start=\"2026\" data-end=\"2049\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"2030\" data-end=\"2049\">5. Applications</strong></h3>\n<ul data-start=\"2050\" data-end=\"2445\">\n<li data-start=\"2050\" data-end=\"2204\" class=\"\" style=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"2052\" data-end=\"2204\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"2052\" data-end=\"2089\">Regular languages &amp; Group Actions</strong>: Certain FSMs that recognize regular languages have underlying <strong data-start=\"2153\" data-end=\"2173\">group structures</strong> (e.g., <strong data-start=\"2181\" data-end=\"2202\">syntactic monoids</strong>).</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"2205\" data-end=\"2326\" class=\"\" style=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"2207\" data-end=\"2326\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"2207\" data-end=\"2229\">Rubik’s Cube &amp; FSM</strong>: The cube's moves form a group, and solving it can be framed as an FSM navigating a state space.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"2327\" data-end=\"2445\" class=\"\" style=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"2329\" data-end=\"2445\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"2329\" data-end=\"2352\">Cryptography &amp; FSMs</strong>: Some cryptographic protocols use FSM-like constructions with group elements as transitions.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 data-start=\"2447\" data-end=\"2465\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"2451\" data-end=\"2465\">Conclusion</strong></h3>\n<p data-start=\"2466\" data-end=\"2744\" class=\"\">FSMs can <strong data-start=\"2475\" data-end=\"2511\">naturally model group structures</strong> by using group elements as states and group operations as transitions. This realization provides insights into computational properties of groups, language recognition, and automata-theoretic interpretations of algebraic structures.</p></div><div class=\"markdown prose w-full break-words dark:prose-invert dark\"><p data-start=\"0\" data-end=\"109\" class=\"\">Yes, <strong data-start=\"5\" data-end=\"73\">any finite group can be realized as a finite state machine (FSM)</strong>, but with some caveats. Here's why:</p>\n<h3 data-start=\"111\" data-end=\"152\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"115\" data-end=\"152\">1. Any Finite Group Can Be an FSM</strong></h3>\n<p data-start=\"153\" data-end=\"217\" class=\"\">A <strong data-start=\"155\" data-end=\"179\">finite group <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span></strong> can always be viewed as an FSM where:</p>\n<ul data-start=\"218\" data-end=\"396\">\n<li data-start=\"218\" data-end=\"264\" class=\"\" style=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"220\" data-end=\"264\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"220\" data-end=\"230\">States</strong> correspond to <strong data-start=\"245\" data-end=\"263\">group elements</strong>.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"265\" data-end=\"339\" class=\"\" style=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"267\" data-end=\"339\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"267\" data-end=\"291\">Inputs (transitions)</strong> correspond to <strong data-start=\"306\" data-end=\"338\">group elements or generators</strong>.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"340\" data-end=\"396\" class=\"\" style=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"342\" data-end=\"396\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"342\" data-end=\"363\">State transitions</strong> follow <strong data-start=\"371\" data-end=\"395\">group multiplication</strong>.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p data-start=\"398\" data-end=\"431\" class=\"\">Thus, the transition function is:</p>\n<span class=\"katex-display\" style=\"\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" display=\"block\"><semantics><mrow><mi>δ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>g</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>g</mi><mo>⋅</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\delta(g, x) = g \\cdot x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 1em; vertical-align: -0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right: 0.03785em;\">δ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right: 0.03588em;\">g</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.6389em; vertical-align: -0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right: 0.03588em;\">g</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⋅</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span></span></span>\n<p data-start=\"463\" data-end=\"484\" class=\"\">for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>g</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">g, x \\in G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.7335em; vertical-align: -0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right: 0.03588em;\">g</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p data-start=\"486\" data-end=\"617\" class=\"\">Since a finite group has a finite number of elements, the FSM has a <strong data-start=\"554\" data-end=\"581\">finite number of states</strong> and operates <strong data-start=\"595\" data-end=\"616\">deterministically</strong>.</p>\n<h3 data-start=\"619\" data-end=\"652\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"623\" data-end=\"652\">2. Cayley Graph as an FSM</strong></h3>\n<p data-start=\"653\" data-end=\"722\" class=\"\">The <strong data-start=\"657\" data-end=\"673\">Cayley graph</strong> of a group provides a direct FSM interpretation:</p>\n<ul data-start=\"723\" data-end=\"866\">\n<li data-start=\"723\" data-end=\"765\" class=\"\" style=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"725\" data-end=\"765\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"725\" data-end=\"751\">Nodes = group elements</strong> (FSM states).</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"766\" data-end=\"821\" class=\"\" style=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"768\" data-end=\"821\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"768\" data-end=\"807\">Edges = labeled by group generators</strong> (FSM inputs).</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"822\" data-end=\"866\" class=\"\" style=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"824\" data-end=\"866\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"824\" data-end=\"865\">Transition function = group operation</strong>.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p data-start=\"868\" data-end=\"978\" class=\"\">Thus, <strong data-start=\"874\" data-end=\"921\">every finite group can be modeled as an FSM</strong> with a transition diagram identical to its Cayley graph.</p>\n<h3 data-start=\"980\" data-end=\"1015\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"984\" data-end=\"1015\">3. Groups That Are Not FSMs</strong></h3>\n<p data-start=\"1016\" data-end=\"1117\" class=\"\">While <strong data-start=\"1022\" data-end=\"1039\">finite groups</strong> can always be FSMs, the same is <strong data-start=\"1072\" data-end=\"1116\">not necessarily true for infinite groups</strong>:</p>\n<ul data-start=\"1118\" data-end=\"1351\">\n<li data-start=\"1118\" data-end=\"1246\" class=\"\" style=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"1120\" data-end=\"1246\" class=\"\">An <strong data-start=\"1123\" data-end=\"1160\">FSM has a finite number of states</strong>, whereas some groups (e.g., <strong data-start=\"1189\" data-end=\"1231\">integers under addition <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{Z}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span></span></span></span></strong>) are infinite.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"1247\" data-end=\"1351\" class=\"\" style=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"1249\" data-end=\"1351\" class=\"\">However, <strong data-start=\"1258\" data-end=\"1310\">some infinite groups can be approximated by FSMs</strong> if we only consider a <strong data-start=\"1333\" data-end=\"1350\">finite subset</strong>.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p data-start=\"1353\" data-end=\"1365\" class=\"\">For example:</p>\n<ul data-start=\"1366\" data-end=\"1601\">\n<li data-start=\"1366\" data-end=\"1483\" class=\"\" style=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"1368\" data-end=\"1483\" class=\"\">The <strong data-start=\"1372\" data-end=\"1419\">additive group of integers (<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{Z}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span></span></span></span>)</strong> cannot be an FSM directly because an FSM has <strong data-start=\"1465\" data-end=\"1482\">finite memory</strong>.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"1484\" data-end=\"1601\" class=\"\" style=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"1486\" data-end=\"1601\" class=\"\">However, the <strong data-start=\"1499\" data-end=\"1542\">cyclic group <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{Z}/n\\mathbb{Z}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 1em; vertical-align: -0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span></span></span></span></strong> (integers modulo <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span>) is <strong data-start=\"1572\" data-end=\"1582\">finite</strong> and can be an FSM.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 data-start=\"1603\" data-end=\"1628\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"1607\" data-end=\"1628\">4. Non-Group FSMs</strong></h3>\n<p data-start=\"1629\" data-end=\"1665\" class=\"\">Not every FSM forms a group because:</p>\n<ul data-start=\"1666\" data-end=\"1854\">\n<li data-start=\"1666\" data-end=\"1760\" class=\"\" style=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"1668\" data-end=\"1760\" class=\"\">FSMs can have <strong data-start=\"1682\" data-end=\"1700\">non-reversible</strong> transitions (while group operations are always invertible).</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"1761\" data-end=\"1854\" class=\"\" style=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"1763\" data-end=\"1854\" class=\"\">Some FSMs have <strong data-start=\"1778\" data-end=\"1798\">absorbing states</strong> (like rejecting states) that break the group structure.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 data-start=\"1856\" data-end=\"1900\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"1860\" data-end=\"1900\">5. Practical Example: FSM as a Group</strong></h3>\n<p data-start=\"1901\" data-end=\"2008\" class=\"\">Consider a <strong data-start=\"1912\" data-end=\"1934\">binary counter FSM</strong> with states representing numbers <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>2</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mo>…</mo><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">0, 1, 2, \\dots, n-1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.8389em; vertical-align: -0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"minner\">…</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">−</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span> (mod <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span>):</p>\n<ul data-start=\"2009\" data-end=\"2143\">\n<li data-start=\"2009\" data-end=\"2065\" class=\"\" style=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"2011\" data-end=\"2065\" class=\"\">The transition function is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>↦</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mspace></mspace><mspace width=\"0.6667em\"></mspace><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mrow><mtext>&thinsp;</mtext><mtext>&thinsp;</mtext><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x \\mapsto x+1 \\mod n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.522em; vertical-align: -0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.6667em; vertical-align: -0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mspace allowbreak\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.6667em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">mod</span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right: 0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"2066\" data-end=\"2140\" class=\"\" style=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"2068\" data-end=\"2140\" class=\"\">This FSM behaves like the <strong data-start=\"2094\" data-end=\"2110\">cyclic group</strong> <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{Z}/n\\mathbb{Z}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height: 1em; vertical-align: -0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p data-start=\"2144\" data-end=\"2223\" class=\"\">Thus, FSMs can <strong data-start=\"2159\" data-end=\"2194\">naturally realize cyclic groups</strong> and other <strong data-start=\"2205\" data-end=\"2222\">finite groups</strong>.</p>\n<h3 data-start=\"2225\" data-end=\"2243\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"2229\" data-end=\"2243\">Conclusion</strong></h3>\n<p data-start=\"2244\" data-end=\"2423\" class=\"\">✅ <strong data-start=\"2246\" data-end=\"2297\">Every finite group can be represented as an FSM</strong><br data-start=\"2297\" data-end=\"2300\">\n❌ <strong data-start=\"2302\" data-end=\"2342\">Not every FSM is necessarily a group</strong><br data-start=\"2342\" data-end=\"2345\">\n❌ <strong data-start=\"2347\" data-end=\"2389\">Not every infinite group can be an FSM</strong> (due to finite states in FSMs).</p>\n<p data-start=\"2425\" data-end=\"2620\" class=\"\">So while FSMs provide a computational model for finite groups, they <strong data-start=\"2493\" data-end=\"2536\">cannot always represent infinite groups</strong> unless additional memory or an extended model (e.g., a pushdown automaton) is used.</p></div>"
}